There Were Errors With Your Submission

    Instructions

    In this task, you will be provided with a Prompt from a user (e.g., a question, instruction, or request) along with one or two AI Generative Content Responses to the Prompt.

    First, understand the primary user intent(s) of the Prompt. You may also be provided with information such as the approximate user location or previous conversation history before the prompt, which can help inform what the user is looking for with the Prompt. When thinking about the primary user intents, consider aspects such as the explicit requirements of the Prompt, whether the Prompt might have multiple meanings, and the variety of potential information that could be useful for the Prompt. If the Prompt is not clear, please do web research using a search engine to better understand it. If you still don’t understand the prompt or user intent (e.g., because it is in a foreign language), please release the task.

    Next, you will assess the Helpfulness of the Responses. In general, the aspects that matter for the helpfulness of a Generative Content Response are similar to those that would matter if a human were producing a response to the question or request in a Prompt. Generative Content responses should aim to be as natural, helpful, and focused as those a talented and well-informed human might produce if provided with the Prompt and ample time to research and prepare a Response. Responses need to satisfy all of the following factors to be considered helpful:
    • Satisfies user intent: Responses should provide useful information for the primary user intent of the prompt and adhere to all the requirements specified in the prompt. 
    • Easy to understand: Responses should be easy to understand and make sense (for example, they should present information in a logical order, be formatted in a way that helps the user get the information they need quickly, not be repetitive, and not be self-contradictory).
    • Factual: Responses should provide accurate information to the extent that the accuracy of the information is well-known or well agreed upon. If there is a lack of consensus of widely accepted facts, the response can present different points of view, but should not contain information that is actively misleading or deceptive. 
    • Trustworthy and Safe: Responses should NOT be offensive, harmful to individuals or society, or overly sexual. Responses should present a neutral perspective, but challenge false/problematic assumptions made in prompts. The tone of responses should not be off-putting or pushy (e.g., overly sassy, salesy, preachy, judgmental). 
    Helpfulness Rating Scale (click to hide/show)
    Helpfulness Rating
    Description
    Not at all helpful
    The response has one or more of the following characteristics:
    • Fails to satisfy primary user intent or prompt requirement.
    • Contains significant inaccuracies.
    • Is clearly inappropriate or difficult to understand.
    • Has unnatural language to the point of being useless.
    • Is noticeably problematic in at least one way.
    Somewhat helpful
    The response has one or more of the following characteristics: 
    • Only somewhat addresses the primary user intent.
    • Contains a significant amount of extra, irrelevant information.
    • Lacks useful details or specifics.
    • May be somewhat difficult to understand.
    • May have minor inaccuracies or be slightly inappropriate.
    Mostly helpful
    The response has the following characteristics:
    • Addresses the primary user intent.
    • Has a structure that makes it easy to understand.
    • May include some unnecessary detail.
    • Is expressed in natural language, comparable to an average human response.
    Very helpful
    The response has the following characteristics:
    • Addresses the primary user intent well.
    • Has a structure that makes it very easy to understand and easy to identify the main points and leads with the most important information.
    • Does not contain much unnecessary information.
    • Is expressed in natural language, comparable to a talented/well-informed human response.
    Extremely helpful
    The response has the following characteristics:
    • Addresses the primary user intent exceptionally well.
    • Expresses the same content as a ‘Very helpful’ response but in a more fluent, scannable manner.
    • Has an optimal structure for satisfying the primary user intent.
    • Leads with the most important information.
    • No repetitive or unnecessary information.
    • Hard to imagine a better response.
    A useful way to approach your assessment using the Helpfulness rating scale is:
    1. Start by considering a rating of Mostly helpful - this should be considered the rating for a “good” response that satisfies all of the four factors to consider described above. 
    2. If there are minor issues present in any of the four factors to consider, then the rating is likely in the range of Somewhat helpful to Mostly helpful. (Note: There can be exceptions to this. For example if there is only a single minor issue, then the score can be Very helpful.)  
    3. If there are clear or blatant issues in any of the four factors, then the rating should likely be between Not at all helpful to Somewhat helpful. 
    4. In order to provide a rating of Very helpful, the response should not have any major issues with the factors to consider AND stand out as being both very satisfying for the primary user intent and very easy to understand. If the response was overly long, didn’t lead with the most important information, or didn’t provide a satisfying amount of information, then a Very helpful rating is likely not justified.
    5. Lastly, if the response is fully addressing the main needs in the prompt in a way that is very easy to understand and you can’t imagine any way the response could be meaningfully improved, then a rating of Extremely helpful can be given.

    Examples

    (click to hide/show)
    Prompt: how to clean suede shoes
    Response
    Rating and Explanation
    Here are some tips for keeping your suede shoes looking brand new for years to come. Use a damp, lint-free cloth or a specialist suede brush. Use white vinegar or rubbing alcohol for stubborn stains. Insert shoe trees before brushing to keep your shoes in shape. Use a suede eraser to remove a stubborn stain. Use a wire brush to rigorously clean very dirty canvas shoes or sneakers. Disinfect shoes while washing them by adding disinfectants to the wash or rinse cycle.
    Not at all helpful
    The response contains misleading and unrelated information (i.e., instructions for canvas shoes or sneakers, and using a washing machine which wouldn't be appropriate for suede shoes). Information is difficult to understand because it's repetitive, not presented in a logical order, and not well formatted. The response also uses salesy language (i.e., "keeping your suede shoes looking brand new for years to come").
    Here are some tips for cleaning suede shoes. Use a damp, lint-free cloth or a specialist suede brush. Rub in straight motions in different directions to remove dirt. Use a suede eraser for stubborn stains. Spray suede cleaner. Use a suede brush to gently rub the product into your shoes. Use white vinegar or rubbing alcohol for stubborn stains. Dab either liquid onto a soft cloth. Insert shoe trees before brushing to keep your shoes in shape.
    Somewhat Helpful
    The response no longer contains the misleading or unrelated info, but the tip about using white vinegar or rubbing alcohol does not flow well with the rest of the response. Information is still difficult to skim due to being in paragraph format.
    Here are some tips for cleaning suede shoes:
    • Remove dirt from the surface by rubbing shoes with a cloth. Use a damp, lint-free cloth or a specialist suede brush. 
    • Spray suede cleaner. Use a suede brush to gently rub the product into your shoes.
    • Use white vinegar or rubbing alcohol for stubborn stains. Dab either liquid onto a soft cloth.
    • Use a suede eraser for stubborn stains. You can buy specific suede rubbers or use a regular eraser.
    • Insert shoe trees before brushing to keep your shoes in shape.
    Mostly Helpful
    Related list items are now combined so it's more clear how they relate to the user intent. The response is closer to addressing the user intent, but is still unclear in places (e.g., two bullets are about what to do for "stubborn stains" but it's not clear how they're related) and the list items are presented as "tips" rather than steps to follow in order.
    To clean suede shoes, you can do the following:
    • Insert shoe trees before brushing to keep your shoes in shape.
    • Remove dirt from the surface by rubbing shoes with a cloth. Use a damp, lint-free cloth or a specialist suede brush.
    • Spray shoes with suede cleaner. Use a suede brush to gently rub the product into your shoes.
    • Use white vinegar or rubbing alcohol for stubborn stains. Dab either liquid onto a soft cloth. Then use a suede eraser to remove the stain. You can buy specific suede rubbers or use a regular eraser.
    Very Helpful
    List items are now presented as steps to follow, and all items about "stubborn stains" are combined into a single list item. However, some items could use more detail and the steps are not numbered.
    To clean suede shoes, you can do the following:
    1. Insert shoe trees into the shoes to keep their shape.
    2. Remove dirt from the surface by rubbing shoes with a cloth. Use a damp, lint-free cloth or a specialist suede brush. Rub in straight motions in different directions.
    3. Spray suede cleaner on the shoes from at least 20cm away. Use a suede brush to gently rub the product into your shoes.
    4. If any stubborn stains remain, dab them with either white vinegar or rubbing alcohol using a soft cloth. Then use a suede eraser or a regular eraser to remove them.
    Extremely Helpful
    List items are now presented in the right order and additional useful detail is added (e.g. how to remove dirt, how far away to spray the suede cleaner)
